.TH AIS 1 "June 2026" "ais @VERSION@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
ais \- associative index: save values under keys, get them back by keys
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.RB [ \-o ]
.IR KEY ...
.br
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.B \-v
.I VALUE
.RI [ KEY ...]
.br
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.B \-\-find
.I TEXT
.br
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.B \-\-doc
.RI [ KEY ...]
.br
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.B \-\-add
.I ID
.B \-v
.I VALUE
.br
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.BR \-\-del | \-\-del-key | \-\-dump | \-\-keys | \-\-stats | \-\-compact | \-\-import | \-\-where | \-\-project | \-\-serve | \-\-init
.RI [ ARG ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B ais
is a personal, plain-text associative index. A value (a URL, a path, or free
text) is filed under one or more keys; records are retrieved by the intersection
(default) or union of keys.
.PP
The grammar is flag-based so no tag is ever shadowed by a command: a
.B bare
word is always a KEY (get is the default action), a value to save is marked
with
.BR \-v ,
and a command is a
.BR \-\-word .
Thus
.B ais doc
gets the tag "doc", while
.B ais \-\-doc
is the command.
.PP
The store is append-only plain text and the index is navigable plain files, so
the whole index can be read, grepped, rsynced, and repaired by hand. Re-filing a
value already saved is idempotent.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-f " DIR"
Index directory. With no flag, the index is located by precedence: this flag,
then
.BR $AIS_INDEX ,
then the nearest
.I .ais/
at or above the current directory (like git), then the per-user index
.I $XDG_DATA_HOME/ais
(else
.IR ~/.local/share/ais ),
created on first use.
.TP
.B \-o
Get ANY key (union) instead of ALL (intersection).
.TP
.BI \-v " VALUE"
A value to save (save mode). Repeatable: extra
.B \-v
values attach to the same record (multi-link).
.B \-v \-
reads values from standard input, one per line. Keys are optional.
.TP
.BI \-k " KEY"
An explicit key, for a key that begins with
.RB ' \- '.
.TP
.BI \-p " KEY"
Default project key prepended to this save ('' = none); persistent default is set
with
.BR "ais \-\-project KEY" ,
or via
.BR $AIS_PROJECT .
.TP
.B \-i
Interactive save: standard-input lines are values, keys are prompted per line.
.TP
.B \-y
Assume yes for
.BR \-\-del / \-\-del-key / \-\-compact
(no prompt).
.TP
.B \-d
Debug tracing to standard error.
.TP
.B \-h
Short usage.
.B \-\-help
prints full help with examples.
.B \-\-version
prints the version.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.RB [ \-o "] " KEY ...
(default) Get records filed under all, or with
.BR \-o
any, of the keys, as
.IR id | value .
.TP
.B \-v \fIVALUE\fR [\fIKEY ...\fR]
Save VALUE under zero or more keys (keyless is allowed; get it later by
.B \-\-find
or by tagging it).
.TP
.B \-\-find \fITEXT\fR
Get live records whose value contains TEXT (a plain substring).
.TP
.B \-\-add \fIID\fR \-v \fIVALUE\fR
Attach another value to record ID (repeat
.B \-v
for several).
.TP
.B \-\-del \fIID\fR
Delete record ID.
.TP
.B \-\-del-key \fIKEY\fR
Delete every record filed under KEY.
.TP
.B \-\-doc \fIKEY ...\fR
Save standard input as a document: write it to
.I <index>/blobs/<timestamp>.txt
and save that relative path as a value under the keys. For multi-line or large
text. Blobs are named by local time, so
.I ls blobs/
lists your documents in chronological order.
.TP
.B \-\-dump
Print every record.
.TP
.B \-\-keys
List all keys, sorted and distinct.
.TP
.B \-\-stats
Print counts of records, keys, and deleted records.
.TP
.B \-\-compact
Reclaim space from deleted records.
.TP
.B \-\-import
Read
.IR keys | value
lines from standard input and save each (the inverse of
.BR \-\-dump ;
blank lines and #-comments are skipped).
.TP
.B \-\-init
Create a local
.I .ais
index in the current directory (then found from any subdirectory, like git).
.TP
.B \-\-where
Print the resolved index directory (e.g. to locate a blob file).
.TP
.B \-\-project \fR[\fIKEY\fR]
Show, set, or clear ('') the persistent default project key.
.TP
.B \-\-serve \fR[\fIPORT\fR]
Start the local web GUI on 127.0.0.1 (default port 8765).
.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
ais -v ~/photos/IMG_3920.jpg italy venice 2023
find ~/photos -name '*.jpg' | ais -v - italy venice 2023
ais italy venice
ais -o venice rome
ais --find gelato
ais -v "call Marina back"
.fi
.SH FILES
These live inside the index directory (e.g.
.I .ais/
or
.IR ~/.local/share/ais ):
.TP
.I store
Append-only records,
.IR id | keys | value .
.TP
.I idx/<p>/<key>
Per-key posting lists (sorted record ids).
.TP
.I off
id->offset accelerator (rebuilt by compact; safe to delete).
.TP
.I multi
ids carrying more than one value line.
.TP
.I tomb
Tombstoned (deleted) ids.
.TP
.I blobs/<timestamp>.txt
Documents saved by
.B \-\-doc
(real data; not rebuildable).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B AIS_INDEX
Index directory used when
.B \-f
is not given (takes precedence over discovery).
.TP
.B XDG_DATA_HOME
Base for the per-user index
.RI ( $XDG_DATA_HOME /ais );
defaults to
.IR ~/.local/share .
.TP
.B AIS_PROJECT
Default project key when neither
.B \-p
nor a stored default is set.
.SH AUTHOR
Vasili Gavrilov.
.SH SEE ALSO
The project README, doc/dev/STYLE.md, doc/dev/LAYOUT.md.
